      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The EX- Prefix: Scrabble's Scoring Engine</h2>
      <p>EX is arguably the most important two-letter combination in competitive Scrabble. At 9 points for just two letters, EX alone is a powerful play. But it also serves as a prefix for dozens of longer words that all inherit that 8-point X boost.</p>
      <p>The beauty of EX- words is their familiarity. EXTRA, EXACT, EXILE, EXPEL, EXERT — these aren't obscure words you need to memorise from a word list. They're everyday vocabulary that happens to score extremely well. This makes the EX- prefix both accessible to beginners and reliable for experts.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">E-Word Strategy Tips</h2>
      <p>With twelve E tiles in the bag, rack management becomes crucial. Here's how to handle them:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Save E for X:</strong> If you have E and know X is still in the bag, consider holding E for the EX combination. The 9-point two-letter play is always available, and longer EX- words score 12-26 points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Dump excess E's quickly:</strong> Drawing 3+ E tiles is common and crippling. Words like EERIE, EMCEE, and EPEE help clear multiple E's in one turn. Don't let them accumulate.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use E as a back hook:</strong> E is the most common back hook in English (-E suffix). MADE, TONE, LIVE, CARE — hundreds of words gain an E at the end for additional scoring.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>EX as a parallel play:</strong> Place EX next to an existing word to form two words simultaneously. The X scoring on a premium square while E connects to an adjacent word is a classic high-level play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ENZYME for Z disposal:</strong> If you hold both E and Z, ENZYME (20 pts) is a strong play. It uses the Z efficiently while clearing one of your many E's.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Two-Letter E-Words</h2>
      <p>E has the richest set of two-letter words, making it the ultimate parallel play enabler:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>EA, ED, EF, EH, EL, EM, EN, ER, ES, ET, EW, EX</strong> — twelve valid two-letter E-words</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>EX</strong> (9 pts) is the highest-scoring two-letter word starting with any vowel</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>EW</strong> (5 pts) is often overlooked but valid — useful when W is nearby on the board</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Managing E-Heavy Racks</h2>
      <p>The biggest challenge with E is overabundance. With 12 tiles in the bag, drawing 3-4 E's is common and painful. Your rack becomes vowel-heavy and inflexible. Prevention is better than cure:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Play E immediately when you have 2+:</strong> Don't hold multiple E's waiting for a perfect play. Get back to one E and refill with consonants.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Exchange if desperate:</strong> Swapping 2-3 E's for fresh tiles is often better than forcing a weak play that scores 8 points while keeping a bad rack.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Know vowel-heavy words:</strong> EERIE (5 pts), EPEE (6 pts), EMCEE (9 pts) — these aren't high-scoring, but they clear E tiles and improve your next draw.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">E in the Endgame</h2>
      <p>Late in the game, E becomes more valuable. As the board fills up, the ability to add -E to existing words (back-hooking) creates scoring opportunities that wouldn't exist with other letters. A single E can turn GRAD into GRADE, PIN into PINE, or TIM into TIME — each hook creating a new word and scoring the full value of the new formation.</p>
      <p>In tight endgames where every point matters, knowing which words accept an -E suffix separates strong finishers from players who get stuck with dead tiles.</p>

